 There are several common causes of null pointer exceptions in Java applications. Here are some of them:

1. Accessing a null variable or object: In this case, you are trying to access a method or property on an object that has been initialized but is now null. To fix this, make sure that you do not assign a value to the variable until after you have checked if it is not null. For example, 

```
public class MyClass {
 private String name;

 public void setName(String name) {
 this.name = name;
 }

 public String getName() {
 return name;
 }
}

MyClass myObject = new MyClass();
myObject.setName("John"); // Assigns a value to the name variable
myObject.getName(); // Throws a null pointer exception
```

2. Using a null reference: In this case, you are trying to access a method or property on an object that has not been initialized yet. To fix this, make sure that you do not assign a value to the variable until after you have checked if it is not null. For example, 

```
public class MyClass {
 private String name;

 public void setName(String name) {
 this.name = name;
 }

 public String getName() throws Exception {
 if (name == null) {
 throw new Exception("Name is null");
 }
 return name;
 }
}

MyClass myObject = new MyClass();
myObject.setName("John"); // Assigns a value to the name variable
String name = myObject.getName(); // Throws a null pointer exception
```

3. Mixing up object and primitive types: In Java, objects and primitives are two different data types. When you try to access a method or property on an object that is of a different data type, you will get a null pointer exception. To fix this, make sure that you only access the object or primitive type that you expect. For example, 

